<h1 class="entry-title post-title">Porting AOSP ROMs using Source Code</h1>
<div class="post-entry">
<p><span style="font-size: 13px;">This will be a rough guide to help people port their favourite <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0" data-hasqtip="0">AOSP</span>
 ROMs using the open source Android code, thereby enabling your device 
to run full ROMs unofficially, built from source. This means you can be 
running the latest version of the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="1">ROM</span> simply by updating your source code and re-building.</span></p>
<p>Some of you maybe thinking “Wait don’t I need to know how to program 
to do this?” Being able to program is not necessarily required (although
 if you are interested in learning, check out the <a href="http://xda-university.com/helpful-links">Helpful&nbsp;Links</a> page) – more important are some hours to research the <a href="http://xda-university.com/as-a-developer/getting-started-with-git-version-control">use of git</a>, looking at some existing <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="2">ROM</span> repository setups like Cyanogenmod and AOKP, and getting a feel as to how a new device is supported.</p>
<p>This guide is for the people who want an <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0" data-hasqtip="3">AOSP</span> <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="4">rom</span>
 that is not currently provided for by a developer. For example your 
device might have Cyanogenmod already available, however you may wish to
 run AOKP, because it allows more customisation without the need to 
decompile and recompile apks etc.</p>
<p>***Disclaimer – Please check if permission is needed before kanging ***<br>
If the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="5">rom</span> that’s been ported is already available for the device and it’s already built from source not a <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="6">rom</span>
 – zip port then please try to add some unique features as there will be
 not much point in porting if there it’s any additional value to what is
 already available and it will just create a massive mess in your device
 development section. However, what this allows us as extreme 
enthusiasts is to reduce the workload for our developers while, giving 
something back to the community in addition to showing your appreciation
 to your device developer/s or power members.</p>
<p>Ok now to the tools needed :<br>
You will need a PC if not you wouldn’t be reading this.<br>
A Github account created with <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="7">Git</span> installed on your system and if possible some knowledge on <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="8">git</span> commands or time to research on them if not known.<br>
For a head start on some commands please refer to the excellent guide on
 XDA by forum moderator eagleeyetom called [Guide] How to use Github and
 can be found by searching on xda developers website.<br>
Some experience with terminal if using Linux<br>
A device and vendor tree for your device<br>
Your <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0" data-hasqtip="9" aria-describedby="qtip-9">AOSP</span> <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="10">rom</span> of choice<br>
Some hours of your time to work on this</p>
<p>This can be done on any platform that has <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="11">git</span>
 supported so windows, linux or mac but you will need linux to build 
android. In this guide I shall be using linux as it’s my preferred 
system and my distribution of choice at the moment Zorin OS 6 as I have 
found it to be the fastest and least resource hungry OS for me so far. 
So all commands in this guide will be using terminal.</p>
<p>For a guide on how to setup an android environment please refer to the guide on how to compile from source found on XDA-U</p>
<p>and for <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="12">git</span> here –<a href="https://help.github.com/articles/set-up-git"> https://help.github.com/articles/set-up-git</a> —-&gt; This is a perfect tutorial and one needed to begin your learning process.</p>
<p>Throughout this guide I shall refer to device <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="13">repo</span> or device tree they mean the same thing. It’s just different ways I like to refer to them. It means the device repository.</p>
<p>Ok now to the tutorial :</p>
<p>Once <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="14">git</span> is setup we now want to look for the device’s <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="15">repo</span> …. If CM or another <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0" data-hasqtip="16">AOSP</span> <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="17">rom</span>
 is already available for your device then look for the github page for 
it by either searching on google or looking for your developer’s github 
page.</p>
<p>Here is how one looks :<img alt="" src="input_files/K7bJmcqjjFFLODaCXyv5f5mmqQTv37mzN4Nk_MMsk_AMeqAk_Ehgj8lXJhpN.png" height="347px;" width="634px;"></p>
<p>As shown above the name setup is usually something like 
android_device_manufacturer_device or device_manufacturer_device. This 
can be used to help find the device tree using a search engine.</p>
<p>Ok once we find that we are going to fork the device <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="18">repo</span> so we can edit it to work with the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0" data-hasqtip="19">AOSP</span> <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="20">rom</span> we are porting. As different roms use different configurations for their setup.</p>
<p>You can fork a project by clicking the fork button on the top right of the github page like so –<img alt="" src="input_files/MLklLSrYlGnJxQF_U9ZZ_E3kzd25f1TZECEJK995i4TvVF9wzIKdT1lrgl7u.png" height="171px;" width="592px;"><br>
Once that’s done we’re going to need to fork your device’s proprietary 
vendor files. Cyanogenmod usually names their repos differently to some 
other teams so when searching for &nbsp;for a vendor <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="21">repo</span>
 for your device on Cyanogenmod it will be 
properietary_vendor_manufacturer, &nbsp;whereas others teams might just 
name it vendor_manufacturer.<img alt="" src="input_files/UrFDjJf5fruwPKKa2E73_ErUo1NfqRkRyVA4I-wLQ2C4XD3Jueg7Q4JPdt73.png" height="289px;" width="619px;"><br>
Now once that’s done go to the github page of the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0" data-hasqtip="22">AOSP</span> <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="23">rom</span> that is being ported and also fork their vendor setup <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="24">repo</span>
 so we can add the device to the setup so it can be called later on when
 we run the . build/envsetup or source build/envsetup.sh command this 
allows us to compile the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="25">rom</span> after when we have selected our target device.</p>
<p>Once that’s done we are now going to start cloning these repos onto 
your local machine so we can modify some files to add our device. Best 
way to do this is create a new directory where all the work is going to 
be done in your home folder and cd into that directory. So mkdir 
directory(name it whatever you want), then cd directory. So for example 
if the name of the new directory was named github then the commands will
 be mkdir github, cd github. Once that’s done navigate to your account 
page on github and clone the repos we forked earlier. To do this we look
 for the ssh url on each <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="26">repo</span> page then we copy it. Then we type <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="27">git</span> clone and paste the url and click enter on the keyboard. This will clone the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="28">repo</span> from your github(remote) to your local(system) allowing you to make changes to the files then upload them back to github.<img alt="" src="input_files/xg96xFx5nSbWSiV9CyIjqSGoIcmCzpmH4yUVfj73mdX5YRRpPbzjqD0pfqRr.png" height="277px;" width="497px;"><br>
<img alt="" src="input_files/1GFQbcdOpZkaDf-gMVy8pwo4qBgeOK0Pahh53JFpPdhIhM7Wqpj9-92ocLES.png" height="327px;" width="489px;"></p>
<p>So when cloning is done the device, vendor tree and the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="29">rom</span>’s
 vendor tree should be present. Now this is the part where we really 
need to switch on our brains. First go back to the github page of the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="30">rom</span>’s
 vendor tree and click on commits now look through them and find one 
where a new device is added. Copy this new configuration and apply it to
 your device by either modifying existing files or creating new ones. To
 ensure no conflicts arise when envsetup.sh is ran try to make the 
product_name different but ensure the product_device and product_model 
are the same as the one in the device tree. <img alt="" src="input_files/QCJioBix8wGUB0vFgs1h7sQmVGENlkpSahtD4fb_wPMA3aqtL6bKw4qbi2do.png" height="287px;" width="535px;"></p>
<p>Once the device has been added what is left is to push the changes to your remote(github) by using the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="31">git</span> push command. This can be done by first using <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="32">git</span> add -A which lets all the new files and changes to be tracked. Then we use the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="33">git</span> commit -am ” message &nbsp;“. E.g <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="34">git</span>
 commit -am “Add defy to the mix”. This adds a commit message which will
 appear on our remote branch with the new changes. Finally we use <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="35">git</span> push origin &lt;branch name&gt; to push the changes to our remote. E.g <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="36">git</span> push origin jellybean</p>
<p>Additionally look at some device setups on the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="37">rom</span>’s github page and see if any changes are needed to make your device configuration compatible with the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="38">rom</span>’s vendor tree. Usually none are need but it depends on how the person or team has setup their vendor tree.</p>
<p>Now this part is the longest and can be the most annoying process as 
we need to find the changes that are necessary to ensure the device 
boots when the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="39">rom</span> has been compiled. This can be done in a number of ways but the best will be to kindly ask one of your device <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="40">rom</span> developer/s or member/s that have created the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0" data-hasqtip="41">AOSP</span> <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="42">rom</span> device tree that is been used to port the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="43">rom</span> you’re porting. Depending on what type of device you have if it has a locked or unlocked <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-41" data-hasqtip="44">bootloader</span> then changes will have to be cherry-picked or merged in different places such as frameworks_base, system_core, etc.<br>
Refer back to the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="45">git</span> guide in the requirements on how to use these commands like <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="46">git</span> cherry-pick, <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="47">git</span>
 merge. I can’t really guide you here as each device is different so 
this is the part where you need your brain at maximum capacity.</p>
<p>Here you will be cloning all the repos where changes need to happen from the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="48">rom</span>’s github page you’re porting. Then cherry-picking and merging these changes. Remember to first add the remote with <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3" data-hasqtip="49">git</span> remote add &lt;name&gt; before you start cherry-picking so the SHA number can be found.</p>
<p>Also remember to add your repos to the platform_mainfest or android(if it’s a CM based <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="50">rom</span>) Additionally, check your device maintainer’s setup to see if any additional repos any needed.<br>
Once that has been resolved push the changes to your remote and make a new directory in your home directory then, <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="51">repo</span> init and <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2" data-hasqtip="52">repo</span> sync, chose your device target with the lunch command and finally use mka to compile the <span class="explanatory-dictionary-highlight" data-definition="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16" data-hasqtip="53">rom</span>. Pat yourself if it compile without errors.</p>
<p>Good Luck and Enjoy your hard work if it’s successful. However, if 
the unfortunate happens then report any issues here and me and the 
others members of XDA will try help out as this is XDA after all where 
we help each other, learn and expand our knowledge of Android.</p>
<p>For an example of what can be achieved look at some of my work and thank you for your time.</p>

				<aside id="explanatory-dictionary-page-definitions">
					<h2> Definitioner </h2>
					<dl>
			
					<dt class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0">AOSP</dt>
					<dd class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-0">The Android Open 
Source Project is the Google project which makes available the source 
code for Android, allowing anyone to build it for themselves. All 
Android ROMs are ultimately based on AOSP at some point in their 
development.</dd>
				
					<dt class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2">Repo</dt>
					<dd class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-2">Repo is used within
 the Android source code to manage multiple git repositories. It can 
synchronise them all, and carry out other actions such as setting up 
your source tree, without having to manually define each repository 
needing downloaded</dd>
				
					<dt class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3">Git</dt>
					<dd class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-3">The Git version 
control system is a distributed version control system, which tracks the
 changes made to some source code. Android and the Linux kernel make 
heavy use of git. 

Git lets multiple authors collaborate on code, and share their changes 
quickly and easily.</dd>
				
					<dt class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16">ROM</dt>
					<dd class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-16">ROM is literally 
“read-only memory” but its usage has changed over time. Today ROM can 
refer to the non-volatile area of a device’s flash memory on which 
read-only data resides or the packed image to be written to that flash 
area.</dd>
				
					<dt class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-41">bootloader</dt>
					<dd class="explanatory-dictionary-definition-41">The bootloader is 
firmware on the phone which runs on every startup. Sometimes it may be 
desirable to change the version of the bootloader, or to load a 
different bootloader entirely to enable different features or a 
completely different OS. The current version of the bootloader can be 
viewed by entering bootloader mode, the process of which is different 
for each and every device or manufacturer.</dd>
				
					</dl>
				</aside>
